Joe’s LeJEPA Experiments

## Objective

The [LeJEPA paper](https://arxiv.org/abs/2511.08544) claims a new approach to pre-training a model in a self-supervised manner, given large amounts of unlabeled data.  The technique has very few hyperparameters, and claims theoretical reasons to believe that the internal representations it produces are useful for a large variety of downstream tasks.

We have large amounts of unlabeled data, and a variety of tasks we need to perform on it, so I wanted to see whether LeJEPA might be useful for us.

Some concerns were raised in [discussions](https://zettaai.slack.com/archives/C056HAABG22/p1764562076001639?thread_ts=1763258752.025889&cid=C056HAABG22) about this paper on Slack:

1. The paper did not test a UNET design, and it seemed uncertain whether the loss could be adapted to this architecture.  
2. There was no existing infrastructure to test the performance of the embeddings once trained.  
3. LeJEPA might require a batch size too large to fit in VRAM.  
4. LeJEPA, if used with ConvNeXt, produces a single embedding vector for an entire input image, and so may have no relevance to our needs at all.

My experiments were designed to investigate these concerns.

## Why LeJEPA?

Quoting the authors (from their [Github repo](https://github.com/rbalestr-lab/lejepa)):

LeJEPA represents a fundamental rethinking of self-supervised learning. Instead of adding more and more heuristics to existing solutions, we erased the blackboard and re-designed a JEPA from scratch with theory-backed first principles. Here are some key benefits:

* **simple**: the core method takes \~50 lines of code, our complete example below is about 130 lines total. LeJEPA has a single hyperparameter (λ). No stop-gradients, no teacher-student networks, no register tokens, ...  
* **provable**: LeJEPA's design is deeply anchored in a few theoretical results ensuring that it uniquely minimizes downstream task risk--we finally have a unified mathematical language to study JEPAs\!  
* **reliable**: LeJEPA works Out-of-the-Box across 60+ architectures (ResNets, ViTs, ConvNets), 10+ datasets, and scales from small models to 1.8B parameters. No painful hyperparameter tuning required.  
* **informative loss**: the training Loss actually means something--boasting 94%+ Spearman correlation between training loss and downstream performance—you can finally do model selection without labeled validation data  
  Because of those benefits, it becomes trivial to perform in-domain pretraining to outperform massive frontier models--even in few-shot or with full finetuning. And because (i) LeJEPA's cross-validation grid is much smaller than other methods, (ii) LeJEPA works with very small mini-batch sizes or datasets, and (iii) LeJEPA's training loss is informative, you can finally pretrain without having access to thousands of high-end GPUs.

## Experiment 0: LeJEPA “Minimal Example”

After cloning Randall Balestriero’s [LeJEPA repo](https://github.com/JoeStrout/lejepa) and fixing a few errors in their “[minimal example](https://github.com/JoeStrout/lejepa/blob/main/MINIMAL.md)” walk-through, I was able to reproduce their demo.  It uses a Vision Transformer backbone and the ImageNette dataset.  I ran this locally on my RTX-4090 GPU, and had to reduce the batch size from 256 to 128 (see [lejepa\_mini\_vit.py](https://github.com/JoeStrout/ML-work-2026/blob/main/lejepa_minimal/lejepa_mini_vit.py) and [config\_lejepa.yaml](https://github.com/JoeStrout/ML-work-2026/blob/main/mec_dec_2025/config_lejepa.yaml)) to fit in VRAM.  It ran somewhat slower for me than for the authors; they claimed this script should complete 800 epochs in about 2 hours, and it took me 7 hours.  But the results looked good:

![][image1]  
LeJEPA balances two losses: “sigreg” is a regularization loss that attempts to push embedding vectors apart, and “inv” is the invariant loss, which tries to make embeddings invariant to small changes (“views”) such as augmentations.  (Note that due to a bug in the Python code, it logged the sigreg loss as both train/inv and train/sigreg above; that was corrected for future runs.)

## Experiment 1: LeJEPA \+ ConvNeXt-V2

The next step was to replace the ViT encoder with a ConvNeXt-V2 encoder, specifically the “convnext\_small” model in [**timm**](https://huggingface.co/timm). The ImageNette task was unchanged.  This performed even better than the ViT version above, with final LeJEPA loss of 0.067, vs 0.083 for ViT, and faster training curves:  
![][image2]  
It also ran substantially faster (4.5 hours vs. 7 hours).  This strongly supports the idea that we don’t need to use a ViT to use LeJEPA; it works just as well or better with a convolutional (ConvNeXt) architecture.  (Training script: [lejepa\_mini\_convnext.py](https://github.com/JoeStrout/ML-work-2026/blob/main/lejepa_minimal/lejepa_mini_convnext.py))

## Experiment 2: LeJEPA+ConvNeXt on MEC data

Next, I wanted to see if we could get similar loss curves when training on MEC data instead of ImageNette images.  I wrote a Pytorch Dataset class that reads from CloudVolume (see [lejepa\_cn\_mec.py](https://github.com/JoeStrout/ML-work-2026/blob/main/mec_dec_2025/lejepa_cn_mec.py)), and returns random 128x128 (XY) patches, with related views.  The patches are drawn from the same cutout used in our MEC ground truth project (5904 x 5904 x 120 voxels), with ¼ of the volume set aside as validation data.

**On “views”:** LeJEPA relies on presenting the network several related “views” of each sample; the network learns to create embeddings that represent what’s invariant among these views.  Views can be augmentations (translations, rotations, scaling, blur, noise), or in the case of time-series data, they are often adjacent or nearby points in time.  As our data is 3D, I chose to use nearby slices (up to \+/- 2 in Z), plus the standard augmentations.  This is based on the assumption that objects visible in one Z-slice will very often be present in nearby Z-slices as well.  Here are some examples showing five different views for each of 3 samples:  
![][image3]

Training this network took about 5.5 hours, and produced very good loss curves:

![][image4]  
![][image5]

This suggests that LeJEPA can learn embeddings on MEC data, and that my selection of views was (at least) not problematic.  In principle, the network at this point contains encodings that represent something meaningful about MEC data.  Specifically: for each sample, LeJEPA produces a single 512-dimensional encoding vector (plus a 16-dimensional projection vector, which is what the LeJEPA sigreg and invariance loss actually operate on).

## Experiment 2b: LeJEPA+ConvNeXt on MEC, 128d embedding

At this point it occurred to me that the 512-dimensional embedding vector might actually be overkill for our needs.  I made the embedding dimension a configurable parameter, and ran the experiment again with 128-dimensional embeddings.  The smoothed loss curves came out like this:  
![][image6]  
So again, it seems to be learning the task very quickly.  While 128 dimensions is still far too many to usefully visualize, the 16-dimensional projection vectors can be represented with little bar graphs.  Here are three samples, five views each, with the projection vectors shown below each one.  Note how the different views for each sample produce very similar projection vectors.  
![][image7]  
You could say that in some sense, that pattern of bars in the bottom row represents “mitochondrion,” while the different pattern seen in the middle row may mean “synaptic vesicles,” etc.  Of course the full 128d embedding vector would be able to hold a much richer representation.

But as Tri correctly pointed out, it’s still producing just a single embedding vector for each input image.  Is there any way this can be useful for our needs?

## Experiment 3: LeJEPA encoder, U-Net decoder

The next experiment investigated a possible solution: keep the LeJEPA encoder (up to the 128d embedding vector, discarding the smaller projection vector), and then hook up a U-Net style decoder, including skip connections from earlier stages in the ConvNeXt network.  The encoder portion would remain frozen, and only the decoder allowed to update during training.  The resulting network (see [mito\_unet\_arch.py](https://github.com/JoeStrout/ML-work-2026/blob/main/mec_dec_2025/mito_unet_arch.py)) has about 60 million parameters, but 50 million of those are frozen after the LeJEPA training, leaving only 10 million to be trained on the task.

For a first task, I wanted to keep it simple: a binary classifier for mitochondria.  I converted the hand-painted semantic classes (see [Slack](https://zettaai.slack.com/archives/C07S0A9HL9K/p1765552078106049?thread_ts=1765212289.192579&cid=C07S0A9HL9K)) into a single segmentation volume with a different ID for each class ([NG link](https://spelunker.cave-explorer.org/#!middleauth+https://global.daf-apis.com/nglstate/api/v1/5271188426194944)).  For this experiment, I used only [class 10](https://spelunker.cave-explorer.org/#!middleauth+https://global.daf-apis.com/nglstate/api/v1/6706960375218176), mitochondria.

Training this mostly-frozen network proceeded much faster than the LeJEPA training, completing an epoch in about 2 seconds on my machine (vs. 4 seconds or so for LeJEPA).  It appeared to learn very well on the training set:  
![][image8]  
…and, as expected, somewhat less well on the validation set:  
![][image9]  
Here are some example outputs (red \= ground truth, blue \= prediction, overlaid in the rightmost column), after 1000 epochs of training (which took about an hour):  
![][image10]  
It tends to have false positives (seeing mitochondria where there are not), but this is 2D, with limited training, and with no fine-tuning of the encoder.  So while not production-quality, I felt that the results showed sufficient promise to continue.

## Experiment 4: LeJEPA+ConvNeXt, 12 semantic classes

My most recent experiment was to see how the same LeJEPA+ConvNeXT frozen encoder would perform with a UNet decoder on 12-class semantic segmentation.  The architecture and training scripts were adjusted ([multi\_unet\_arch.py](https://github.com/JoeStrout/ML-work-2026/blob/main/mec_dec_2025/multi_unet_arch.py)) and [multi\_seg\_train.py](https://github.com/JoeStrout/ML-work-2026/blob/main/mec_dec_2025/multi_seg_train.py)) to use all 12 classes in the [semantic labels volume](https://spelunker.cave-explorer.org/#!middleauth+https://global.daf-apis.com/nglstate/api/v1/5271188426194944).  Again the training curves look good (this is \~1000 epochs, which took a little more than an hour):  
![][image11]  
On the validation set, IOU curves look good, though the loss curves show a bounce:  
![][image12]  
Claude thinks the bounce in the loss curves reflects probability calibration, and not classification accuracy, which is better measured by IOU.  Some sample predictions:  
![][image13]  
So, noisy.  After the holidays I tried running for an additional 1000 epochs, but the results did not improve appreciably.  Results after 2000 epochs (total) can be viewed [in Neuroglancer](https://spelunker.cave-explorer.org/#!middleauth+https://global.daf-apis.com/nglstate/api/v1/5354767818686464); layer 2 (multiseg inference) is the network predictions, while layer 3 (mec\_sem\_cls) is the ground truth.

## Discussion

The purpose of these experiments was to see whether LeJEPA holds any promise for our work.  I did almost no optimization of architecture or hyperparameters, choosing only the simplest or most expedient option at every point:

* LeJEPA based on the author’s “minimal example” script  
* fixed learning rate  
* arbitrarily chosen 128-dimensional embedding vector  
* off-the-shelf and small ConvNeXt-V2 backbone (timm’s “convnext\_small”)  
* limited training volume (5904 x 5904 x 120 voxels)  
* simple UNet decoder  
* no fine-tuning of encoder (which comprised 5/6th of the weights) on the task  
* a few hours of training on a single GPU

…and despite all that, it was able to learn a recognizable (if somewhat noisy) semantic segmentation of the data.

This suggests that LeJEPA is indeed applicable to our data, and is learning something useful from the self-supervised training phase.

Because we have so much raw image data — but very little ground truth — leveraging self-supervised learning could be a big win.  We might be able to train a foundation model on a variety of EM data (and perhaps a separate one for LICONN data), and then bring that to bear on each project, producing better results with less per-project training.  Or, if it works better to freshly train the encoder on each project (so that the model can focus on the particular resolution and sample quirks of that set), it may still be worthwhile if it produces better results due to training on the huge volume of unlabeled data.
